s=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span></p>\n<p>With our image files renamed, we are nearly ready to compile them into a video. First we need to decide how to crop our video. Unless you set your camera to shoot in a standard video frame size, you’ll need to adjust the crop manually. These next few steps require some command line magic, so it may look scary, but it’s pretty straightforward. The easiest way I’ve found to determine the crop parameters is with <a href=\"https://www.gimp.org/\">Gimp</a>, so open any one of your frames in Gimp. With the crop tool selected, check the “Fixed” option and set it to “Aspect ratio”. For the sake of demonstration, I’m assuming we are going to output a 1080p video, so in the field just below the “Fixed” checkbox, enter “16:9”.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 210px; \"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 94.28571428571429%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/svg+xml,%3csvg%20xmlns=\\'http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\\'%20width=\\'400\\'%20height=\\'377\\'%20viewBox=\\'0%200%20400%20377\\'%20preserveAspectRatio=\\'none\\'%3e%3cpath%20d=\\'M3%20189v188h5V0H3v189m393%200a6723%206723%200%20002%200%206723%206723%200%2000-2%200M80%2012l-65%201h86a2707%202707%200%2000-21-1m110%2034v32h186v150a4239%204239%200%20002-1c0-136%200-150-2-150l-93-1h-91l-1-3a449%20449%200%2001-1-27M11%20197a6166%206166%200%20002%200%206166%206166%200%2000-2%200M25%2030l-1%2015c-1%2014-1%2015%201%2016h30l2-1V45l-1-15H25m323%200v19c2%201%2016%202%2019%200%202-2%203-14%201-18-2-2-3-2-10-2l-10%201M25%2046v14h31V31H25v15m326-14c-2%201-2%2011-1%2014%201%202%2013%203%2015%201l1-7-1-8h-14M68%2035c-2%201